When displaying these problems, developers should show the thought process. 
Here I show the brute force solution and the cleaner solution. 


Note the similarities:
1. Intialization - Creating that first empty node handles the zero condition
2. Deletion - Basic principle of a linked list

--------------------------------

**BRUTE FORCE**
The brute force uses getting a count first. 
It's not pretty but the biggest issue is looping through the list twice. 

```
public class Solution {
    public ListNode RemoveNthFromEnd(ListNode head, int n) {
        var start = new ListNode(0);
        var node = start;
        node.next = head;

        // Get Count
        var count = GetCount(head);

        // Iterate to node to Skip
        for(int i = 0; i < count - n; i++) {
            node = node.next;
        }

        // Remove Node
        node.next = node.next.next;

        return start.next;
    }

    private int GetCount(ListNode head) {
        var count = 0;
        var current = head;
        while(current != null) {
            count++;
            current = current.next;
        }
        return count;
    }
}
```

------------------------------------------------------------------

**DOUBLE POINTER**

If you understand the method to get the count, this becomes more feasible. 

The solution that everyone has posted repeatedly. 
1. Fast pointer - exactly n ahead slow
2. Slow pointer - the pointer that will hit length - n

```
public class Solution {
    public ListNode RemoveNthFromEnd(ListNode head, int n) { 
        var start = new ListNode(0);
        var slow = start;
        var fast = start;
        slow.next = head;

        // Fast is n in front of slow
        for(int i = 0; i <= n;  i++)   {
            fast = fast.next;
        }

        // When Fast is at end, Slow is at end - n
        while(fast != null) {
            slow = slow.next;
            fast = fast.next;
        }

        // Remove Node
        slow.next = slow.next.next;

        return start.next;
    }    
}
```

