# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The code leverages the pattern observed in Pascal's Triangle, where each element in a row can be obtained by adding the two elements directly above it.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Create an ArrayList named result to store the elements of the row.
2. Handle the edge case where rowIndex is less than 0 by returning an empty list.
3. Add the first element, which is always 1, to the result list.
4. Iterate from row 1 to rowIndex (inclusive):
- Within each row, iterate backwards starting from the second-to-last element to the first element.
- Update each element by setting it to the sum of the current element and the next element in the result list.
- This operation effectively calculates the value at each position in the current row using the values from the previous row.
5. After the inner loop completes, add the last element (which is always 1) to the result list.
6. Return the result list.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of the code is O(rowIndex^2). This is because for each row from 1 to rowIndex, the inner loop iterates from the second-to-last element to the first element, which takes roughly rowIndex/2 iterations on average. Therefore, the overall time complexity is proportional to the sum of 1 + 2 + 3 + ... + rowIndex, which is equivalent to rowIndex * (rowIndex + 1) / 2, resulting in O(rowIndex^2) time complexity.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity is O(rowIndex) since the size of the result list is equal to rowIndex + 1, which stores the elements of the generated row. The additional space required is negligible compared to the size of the result list, making the space complexity O(rowIndex).  

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> getRow(int rowIndex) {
        ArrayList<Integer> result = new ArrayList<Integer>();
        if (rowIndex < 0)
            return result;
        result.add(1);
        for (int i = 1; i <= rowIndex; i++) 
        {
            for (int j = result.size() - 2; j >= 0; j--) 
            {
                result.set(j + 1, result.get(j) + result.get(j + 1));
            }
            result.add(1);
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

