# Intuition Pascal's Triangle II
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
utilizing the concept of nCr $${N}\choose{k}
$$

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
we know from binomial theorem that $${N}\choose{R}
$$ = $${N}\choose{N-R}$$  
1st element is 1 
2nd element is N
3rd element is N*(N-1)/2  ie a[1]*(N-1)/2
4th element is  N*(N-1)(N-3)/(2*3) ie a[3]*(n-2)/3 

this way we can build till (N+1)/2 th element then we can copy the value of rth to N-r index

# Complexity
- Time complexity:$$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:$$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> getRow(int rowIndex) {
        if(rowIndex==0) return {1};
        if(rowIndex==1) return {1,1};
        vector<int> result(rowIndex+1, 1);
        int m=rowIndex/2;  //getting the mid element index as it's zero based index. Had it been N given then (N+1)/2
        result[1]=rowIndex;
        for(int i=2; i<=m; i++ ){
            result[i] =( ((long)result[i-1]) * (rowIndex-i+1) )/i; //(used (long) to avoid Integer OverFlow)
        }
        int r=rowIndex;
        int l=0;
        while(r>l) result[r--]=result[l++]; // rth value to (N-r)
        return result;

    }
};
```

