# Intuition
1 -We could go ahead and check every window of size k, but this is going to take to long. Thus we need to use our knowledge of the previously checked window.

2- Set is a good tool, when we want to check for similar values, but it doesn't keep any knowledge of what's been added when

3- Queue is a good way to know what was the oldest element added, but not too quick to look for matches..

The idea is to sacrifice some memory to use both structures.

# Approach
Iterate nums from head to end. Add every new number to map, where key- number, value - index of number. If number in map- check condition that current index of number minus index of number from map less or equal "k". If true- return true. If false, rewrite value of current number in map by current index.
If iteration is ended - return false

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n^2)

- Space complexity:
O(n)

# Code
```
/**
 * @param {number[]} nums
 * @param {number} k
 * @return {boolean}
 */
var containsNearbyDuplicate = function(nums, k) {
    for(let i = 0; i <= nums.length-1; i++){
        let j = nums.length -1;
        while(i < j){
            if(nums[i] == nums[j] && Math.abs(i - j) <= k){
                return true
            }
            j--;
        }

    }
    return false
};
```

