solutions.content:
I'll go from an unimproved to the improved version.

Main Idea (2-pass) -
* Store the indices of same nums[i] and compare them.
* **We need to only compare the adjacent ones as we need abs(i-j) less than/equal to k. Having to compare values which are not adjacent will only give a worse answer.**
* Thus we can store a map of vectors, where a value will point to the different indices, stored in a vector. In other words, we need to have a `map<int, vector<int>>`  and then iterate compute for all adjacent elements of different vectors in the map.
* Time Complexity : `O(n)` Since the **size of all vectors which we are iterating sums up to the actual size of the array.**
* Space Complexity : `O(n)` Additional space due to the map used.

Code :
```c++
class Solution {
public:
    bool containsNearbyDuplicate(vector<int>& nums, int k) {

        int n = nums.size();

        map<int, vector<int>> mp;
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++) 
            mp[nums[i]].push_back(i);

        map<int, vector<int>> :: iterator itr;

        for(itr = mp.begin(); itr != mp.end(); itr++) {
            int sz = (itr->second).size();
            for(int i=0; i<sz-1; i++)
                if(abs(itr->second[i] - itr->second[i+1]) <= k)
                    return true;
        }

        return false;
    }

};
```

Idea for (1-pass) Solution :
* Since we only need to compare adjacent values and indices are increasing as we traverse ahead, **it is only required to store the greatest index of num[i] encountered till then.** Thus, `mp[nums[i]] = idx;`
* If we encounter the the same element with different index we just calculate `abs(i - mp[num[i]])`. If it is `<= k` return `true`, else we just update the map with `i` for next comparison.
* Time Complexity : `O(nlogn)`. **One Pass is needed. + We need to check .find() which is logarithmic. in a map**
* Space Complexity : `O(n)`. Size of the map equal total number of unique numbers. 

Code :
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool containsNearbyDuplicate(vector<int>& nums, int k) {

        int n = nums.size();

        map<int, int> mp;
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++) {
			// element already exists
			// check takes O(logn) in a map and O(1) in unordered map 
            if(mp.find(nums[i]) != mp.end()) {
                if(abs(mp[nums[i]] - i) <= k)
                    return true; // condition satisfied
                else
                    mp[nums[i]] = i;
					// just update with latest index for next check.
            }

			// adding new element
            else 
				mp[nums[i]] = i; 
        }

        return false;
    }
};
```

Final Optimization Step -
**Likewise, we can use `unordered map<int, int>` in the 1-pass case and Time Complexity reduces to `O(n)`.**

