# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

We need our i and j to be at max distance of k. Thus we can use a Sliding Window in which we can use a map to store whether we found an element before or not in constant time, reducing our time complexity.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

1) Initialise an unordered map (HASH MAP) and store in the elements in subarray nums[0...k-1].

2) Initialise two pointers i and j to 0 and k respectively.

3) Check whether the jth element already exists in our map? If yes, then return true, else continue.

3) Add the jth element and remove the ith element from the map. Remember we can do this is constant time by making use of a boolean map.

4) We continue this untill j crosses n.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool containsNearbyDuplicate(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int n = nums.size(),i = 0,j = 0;
        unordered_map<int,bool> found;
        while(j<k && j<n){
            if(found[nums[j]])
                return true;
            found[nums[j++]] = true;
        }
        while(j<n){
            if(found[nums[j]])
                return true;
            found[nums[j]] = true;
            found[nums[i]] = false;
            i++;
            j++;
        }
        return false;
    }
};
```

